ἐ 9 De tuo auam negocio] The decree relative to Sicyon, ³ on the subject of which cf. Ep. 13.1 and the note on the passage. The special object of the decree in question is nowhere mentioned by Cicero. Ernesti considers that it was simply a refusal on the part of the Senate to interfere between an individual and the members of a free state-an explana· tion which is certainly in accordance with the words which follow: tu si tuis blandities tamen a Sicyoniis ramulorum aliquid expresseris, velim me sareas certiorem. On the other hand, Schi'rtz and Matthiae are of opinion that the object of the decree was to exempt the Sicyonians, in part at any rate, from the burden of taxation. A careful consideration of the passages in which the subject is mentioned, more especially of §4 of the ensuing letter, has induced me to accept the latter as in all probability the correct view
